# New solution update! - We are going to bind mount our scattered files
# Bind mounting will set an illusion of the scattered file on the repo
# and will bind them too allowing for editting in both locales

# If U bind your files U might as well work from your repo now, and
# enjoy the structure.

# I'll assume the target dir is already tracked by git
#		sudo - required for mounting capabilities
#		mount - the actual mount command
#		--bind - UNIX style option for binding the files/dirs
#		"path/to/scattered/file" - original location of file
#		"path/to/repo/dir/file" - dir is where file is in repo
# For files
# sudo mount --bind /path/to/scattered/file /path/to/repo/dir/file
# For dirs
# sudo mount --bind /path/to/scattered/dir/ /path/to/repo/dir/

# Better yet;

# set your mounts over in /etc/fstab - Will handle mounting and 
#                 and unmounting during login and logout.

# Make sure U that the repo-path and subsequent files exist!

# <scattered-path> <repo-path> <type=none> <options=bind> <dump=0> <pass=0>

# /scattered/path   /repo/path  none	    bind	   0	    0

# slight CAVEAT!: If U run `lsblk` U will see the mounts, come to think
# about it, U could use it to track your mounts, origins won't be shown


# And now U have one file in 2 places, I guess the number could vary
# depending on how crazy U are willling to go
